\begin_layout Standard
This chapter gives a brief overview of the important theorems and parameters
 for understanding the dynamics of resonant systems, such as the OAPA.
 In particular, those relevant to mechanical resonators with masses in the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu g-ng$
\end_inset

 range, which are known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

microresonators
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The main properties of note for a microresonator are their resonant frequencies
, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-factors, power spectra and mode shapes; these are discussed in the sections
 below.
 The resonators of interest to this thesis are a silicon nitride membrane
 of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $3mm\times3mm\times50nm$
\end_inset

 and a silicon mirror of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $1mm\times1mm\times60\mu m$
\end_inset

, which are shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:microtechno"

\end_inset

, and are discussed at length in Chapters 3 and 4.
\end_layout

