\begin_layout Standard
Near resonance, the dynamics of a vibrating membrane, such as the silicon
 nitride membrane discussed in Chapter 4, can be described by the wave equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Waves1977"

\end_inset

.
 For a square, lossless membrane in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 plane, with edges (i.e.
 boundary conditions), located at 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0),\,(0,B),\,(A,0),\,(A,B)$
\end_inset

, the transverse motion of the membrane 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,y,t)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the partial differential equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla^{2}u(x,y,t)=\frac{1}{c^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}u(x,y,t)}{\partial t^{2}}.\label{eq:wave eqn}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is known as the wave equation.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\sqrt{F_{T}\rho}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{T}$
\end_inset

 is the tension force and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is mass per unit area.
 The solutions to this are of the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u(x,y,t)=A\, sin(\frac{n_{1}\pi x}{A})sin(\frac{n_{2}\pi y}{B})cos(rct+\epsilon),\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1},n_{2}\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$
\end_inset

 and are known as the mode numbers, and 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}=\sqrt{\frac{n_{1}^{2}}{A^{2}}+\frac{n_{2}^{2}}{B^{2}}}\pi^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The first three solutions to this equation are shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:First 3 wave eqn"

\end_inset

.
 The frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{n_{1},n_{2}}$
\end_inset

 of vibration is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $rc/2\pi$
\end_inset

, or
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\omega_{n_{1},n_{2}} & = & \sqrt{\left(\frac{n_{1}^{2}}{A^{2}}+\frac{n_{2}^{2}}{B^{2}}\right)\frac{F_{T}}{4\rho}}.\label{eq:mn}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

In a square membrane with side length 
\begin_inset Formula $L=A=B$
\end_inset

, this simplifies to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\omega_{n_{1},n_{2}} & = & \omega_{1,1}\,\sqrt{\frac{n_{1}^{2}+n_{2}^{2}}{2}},\label{eq:wave reln}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the mass of the membrane.
 It is convenient to refer to each of these resonances in terms of their
 mode mode numbers, which are denoted in this thesis as a bracketed pair,
 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{1},n_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
